In this case, you can use CASE WHEN.

It should look like this, there are plenty of resources online if you want to go deeper into it.
```
select customer_name, id, age, 
(case 
when (age between 0 and 14) then &#39;0-14&#39;
when (age between 15 and 25) then &#39;15-25&#39;
when (age between 26 and 50) then &#39;26-50&#39;
end) as age_group
from tableName;
```

You can use `table_name.*` (or give the table an alias and use `alias.*`) to get all the columns (or you could list all the columns in the select clause) and then use a `CASE` statement to generate the `age_group` column:

```sql
SELECT customer.*,
       CASE
       WHEN age &lt;= 14 THEN &#39;0-14&#39;
       WHEN age &lt;= 25 THEN &#39;15-25&#39;
       WHEN age &lt;= 50 THEN &#39;26-50&#39;
       ELSE &#39;51+&#39;
       END as age_group
FROM   customer
```

Another approach would be to create a [virtual column][1] to obscure the `CASE` expression:

    ALTER TABLE customer ADD age_group as 
      (CASE
       WHEN age &lt;= 14 THEN &#39;0-14&#39;
       WHEN age &gt;= 15 and age &lt;= 25 THEN &#39;15-25&#39;
       WHEN age &gt;= 26 and age &lt;= 50 THEN &#39;26-50&#39;
       ELSE &#39;51+&#39;
       END
      );
Then you can simply:

    SELECT * FROM customer;

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/database/121/ADFNS/adfns_editions.htm#ADFNS1328

